<subSubSection box="[199,1116,797,821]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1436,617,1002]" box="[199,1116,797,821]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis box="[199,333,797,821]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,326,797,821]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Etymology</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
The new subgenus is named for its occurrence in saline environment.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1436,617,1002]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis box="[199,315,833,857]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,833,857]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Remarks</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
The slightly modified first and especially the second leg, with the sixth segment distally tapering and with multiple irregular constrictions at the ventral margin is very distinctive and will separate members of the subgenus from representatives of all other other subgenera of this genus. Sexual dimorphism in I-L has not been reported in other limnesiids and a modified second leg is found only in 
<taxonomicName authority="Smit" authorityName="Smit" authorityYear="1994" box="[965,1178,941,965]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Xenolimnesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Actinedida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[965,1117,941,965]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Xenolimnesia</emphasis>
Smit
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[1249,1365,941,965]" name="Cameroon" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Cameroon</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Smit, H." pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="5 - 11" refId="ref34210" refString="Smit, H. (1994) New species of water mites from West Africa (Acari, Hydrachnellae), including a checklist of species recorded from Cameroon. Storkia, 3, 5 - 11." type="journal article" year="1994">Smit 1994</bibRefCitation>
), a genus having the three distal segments highly modified.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
